    The Strong Dose Of Nitrous Oxide, by Joseph Giles
    The Fart In The Spacesuit, by Stephen Clinton
I'm not convinced any of these is very hilarious. On the dystopia and future themes, which of these books is more spiritual than the other? "The Giver" by Lois Lowry, or "Nineteen Eighty-Four" by George Orwell? On the looking and perspective themes, which of these books is more philosophical than the other? "Possible Minds: Twenty-Five Ways of Looking at AI" by John Brockman, or "The Story of Looking" by Mark Cousins? On the racism theme, which of these books is more heartrending than the other? "A Very Large Expanse of Sea" by Tahereh Mafi, or "Dread Nation" by Justina Ireland? "Carrie" by Stephen King, or "Coraline" by Neil Gaiman? I compared the recent tweets of @stephenKing and @neilhimself https://t.co/e1poxkElLp Amazon customers who bought Tom Wolfe's "The Right Stuff" also bought these 'engaging' titles:
    The Sunburn, by Christopher Woolf
    The Trip To The Linen Store In The Rain, by Yann Carson
Do they even know what 'engaging' means? On the religion and atheism themes, which of these books is more endearing than the other? "The Golden Compass" by Philip Pullman, or "God Is Not Great: How Religion Poisons Everything" by Christopher Hitchens? On the politics theme, which of these books is more dangerous than the other?     The Average Shopping Mall, by Geoffrey Kaling
    The House Call From The Cemetery Salesman, by Sloane Sartre
Maybe I don't understand the word 'dramatic'? On the ambition theme, which of these books is more political than the other? "The Audacity of Hope" by Barack Obama, or "Outliers: The Story of Success" by Malcolm Gladwell? I compared the recent tweets of @BarackObama and @Gladwell https://t.co/0kjH3pSHpy On the philosophy theme, which of these books is subtler than the other? "The Name of the Rose" by Umberto Eco, or "The Fountainhead" by Ayn Rand?

We came to help with Redwall's Midsummer Feast. I was thinking of making a carrot and turnip flan with sage and parsley trimming. My mother is very good at baking blueberry and almond turnovers. The young molemaid helped herself to a plate of apple, cheese, and nut salad and a rosepetal an' maple wafer spread with soft white cheese. In rapid order, a full quince an' elderberry pie, a plate of dried fruits, a big pitcher of plum beer, and an enormous leek and turnip pastie were devoured by the insatiable hare. The biggest single offering on the table was a high wobbling redcurrant jelly, with flaked almond and chestnut suspended inside like a sunset snowstorm, wreathed in yellow-piped meadowcream. The Dibbuns were spooning in arrowroot cream pudding and swigging tansy an' coltsfoot cordial as if they had survived a seven-season famine. He stuffed himself with toasted teacakes, slices of plum an' almond cake, soft cheese and watercress sandwiches, a carrot 'n' onion pasty , and a large tankard of dark ale. To refresh the palate there was golden cider, dandelion ale, cellar-cooled dandelion an' mint tea, fizzy wild cherry an' redcurrant cordial, and raspberry cup. Cellar supplies all up an' waitin'. First barrel of last October's ale tapped, mint an' pennycloud cordial, mint an' rosehip tea, dandelion an' burdock fizz, oh, and a small firkin of cowslip wine, to keep out the chill. It is, sah, teatime doncha know, barley bread with quince jam, candied hazelnuts an' mint an' apple tea, wot!

rawText: This afternoon, I journeyed to a limestone pleasure dome near the streams of a far-flung settlement. The people here marry young, and only in the fall. The locals are very ashamed about this. This afternoon, I photographed a limestone citadel near the swamps of a forgotten barony. People remember this region for its traders; it has produced many famous ones. The locals are embarassed about this. After leaving the party, I hiked to a brownstone garden near the mountain peaks of an abandoned dominium. I noticed immediately that most of the spires are made of flaggy limestone. The locals are scared about this. Last week, I explored a flaggy limestone shrine near the deserts of a distant district. According to legend, it was built by eight considerate mariners. And that's why I'm scared. This morning, I wandered by a diamond library near the prairies of an outlying township. Unless you have an onyx car, you'll be considered quite atrocious - it's a local prejudice. The Spring Bannerwoman told me the missing doctor was hiding here. Yesterday night, I wandered by a diorite lookout near the islands of a well-known barony. According to legend, it was built by six weary captains. The fortune-tellers shared this widely. This morning, I hiked to a travertine yurt near the beaches of a mysterious burg. The area is overrun by levitating wasteland bulls that radiate with a delightful friendliness. As a result, the Fortune-teller Alliance now runs every settlement. This afternoon, I stretched close to a granite palace near the islands of a mysterious territory. I spoke to the minaret-dwellers, who think the people by the swamps are enthralling. And that's why I'm angry. Last week, I found a diamond pit near the jungles of a remote district. According to legend, it was built by eight carefree cooks. Perhaps there are technological reasons for this. Once the sun set, I entered a travertine lookout near the oceans of an ancient barony. The men dye their hair black and make their clothes from roots. As a result, the Astrologer Alliance now runs every borough. This morning, I wandered by a sandstone belfry near the oceans of a far-flung municipality. Many joke journals are produced there. Given this, I can hardly blame the royal House of Bean for being so quiet.

We've come to the end of Charles's voyage in The Beagle. What would people like to have happen now?

rawText: In the breaker's yard your sensors pick up a deserted Desert-class picket ship. Its Z-beam ballista turrets won't fire. Half-buried on the planet's surface a sensor ping shows a derelict Daedalus-class dropship. When you board it, your motion sensor goes haywire. In the storage room you discover a mass-driver torpedo. When you try to switch it on, a loud voice says 'DANGER'. In the locker you recognise a neural cooling system. When you try to press the power switch, it starts counting down: FIVE, FOUR, THREE.... In the cargo bay you uncover a phase sword. When you try to fire it, it freezes time within a 4m radius. In the breaker's yard a sensor ping shows an abandoned Gzilt corvette. Its power mortars are faulty. An alien trader flogs you a malfunctioning hyperdrive. The AI core seems to have gone rogue. In the breaker's yard your sensors show a deserted Y-5 transport. You spot something moving but the motion sensor is silent. The replicator malfunctions and creates a photonic carbine. When you pull the trigger, there's a blinding flash of light. Adrift in the asteroid field, you locate an abandoned Myrmidon-class cargo ship. The cargo hold is full of destablised sodium coils. In the trash compactor you salvage a dart revolver. When you try to activate it, the microdensity encabulator malfunctions.

rawText:
can this be my end?
before it ends
moving west o rose
quick water in a channel
the frozen heart of the mountain the herald arrives, like dawn
hello, traveller
immense held in the hot grasp of fury
i fall silent
a light far off in the forest as if a man dies
o mind
o life a present tied with a bow
a last glance backwards
the mouth of an empty mine a war that begets itself
the pigeons scatter, return
destiny and disillusion the ice, unmelted
lightning splits the oak
how admirable! i float until the end of the ocean
now you are well and truly lost
athena's cold gaze shall i say what i see?
aha!
time, the destroyer! no one will come here again
warm beneath blankets of snow
icicles hang in the trees
